Figure 4a shows that when a small SAN (radius r = 0.27 cm) was combined with the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\epsilon {\mathbf{ = }} - \frac{1}{2}$$\end{document}ϵ=-12 variant, spontaneous SAN activity was silenced. In this case the electrotonic load of the surrounding atrial tissue prevents the current generated by the SANCs from being sufficient to generate a propagating depolarization wave, and thus pacemaking ceases. Such a sharp loss of sinus excitation would be associated with severe (class 1) SAN dysfunction. In an intermediate-sized SAN (radius r = 0.34 cm), by contrast, all variants show a stable pacemaking (data not shown).
